04378nam a22006735i 9781487571931DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191997onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875719317 a10.3138/97814875719312doi  a(DE-B1597)537007  a(OCoLC)1125190223  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aANT0170002bisacsh04a749.211/09/042211 aWright, Virginia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModern Furniture in Canada :b1920-1970 /cVirginia Wright. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPlates -- tIntroduction -- t1. Introduction from Europe -- t2. The Furniture Professions -- t3. Craft and Design -- t4. Architects and Advocacy -- t5. Committees, Competitions, and Commissions -- t6. Design Issues -- t7. In the Spotlight -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tSources of Illustrations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanada's furniture history includes hitherto unrecognized work of international significance in modern design. In this richly illustrated study, Virginia Wright brings such accomplishments to the fore, employing archival photographs and original documentation to trace the development of professional furniture design, design education, and design advocacy in Canada from 1920 to 1970. Chief among the milestones were the production in Ontario in the mid-1920s of moulded plywood seating for assembly halls, and the world's first moulded plastic furniture produced in prototype by the National Research Council in 1946 - three years before the more famous designs by Charles Eames in the United States.Within a narrative framework, Wright charts the development of modern design from its first appearance in an Eaton's department store, with pieces brought from the Paris Exposition of 1925, through its stealthy entry into Canadian homes, to its establishment as a dominant style. She shows how the introduction of modern industrial materials such as steel tube, rubber, and plywood into the production of commercial and institutional furnishings, and their incorporation into modern decor, reached a wide public through exhibitions and the media. Wright also reveals the relative neglect of this facet of Canada's art history by its museums and galleries, which, after featuring new furniture made in Canada, failed to acquire any for their own permanent exhibitions or study collections.The first account of Canada's innovative furniture design and fabrication of the period, Modern Furniture in Canada, 1920 to 1970 opens the door to a whole new field of study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFurniture designzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aANTIQUES & COLLECTIBLES / Furniture.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148757193140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487571931423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487571931.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999c1933d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK